.ansibold {

}

}

}

  color: gray;
}
/* and light for background, for the same reason */
.ansibgblack {
  background-color: black;
}
.ansibgred {
  background-color: red;
}
.ansibggreen {

}

div.cell {
  /* Old browsers */
  display: -webkit-box;
  -webkit-box-orient: vertical;
  -webkit-box-align: stretch;
  display: -moz-box;
  -moz-box-orient: vertical;
  -moz-box-align: stretch;
  display: box;
  box-orient: vertical;
  box-align: stretch;
  /* Modern browsers */
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  align-items: stretch;
  border-radius: 2px;
  box-sizing: border-box;
  -moz-box-sizing: border-box;
  -webkit-box-sizing: border-box;
  border-width: 1px;
  border-style: solid;
  border-color: transparent;
  width: 100%;
  padding: 5px;
  /* This acts as a spacer between cells, that is outside the border */
  margin: 0px;
  outline: none;
  border-left-width: 1px;
  padding-left: 5px;
  background: linear-gradient(to right, transparent -40px, transparent 1px, transparent 1px, transparent 100%);
}
div.cell.jupyter-soft-selected {
  border-left-color: #90CAF9;
  border-left-color: #E3F2FD;
  border-left-width: 1px;
  padding-left: 5px;
  border-right-color: #E3F2FD;
  border-right-width: 1px;
  background: #E3F2FD;
}
@media print {
  div.cell.jupyter-soft-selected {
    border-color: transparent;
  }
}
div.cell.selected {
  border-color: #ababab;
  border-left-width: 0px;
  padding-left: 6px;
  background: linear-gradient(to right, #42A5F5 -40px, #42A5F5 5px, transparent 5px, transparent 100%);
}
@media print {
  div.cell.selected {
    border-color: transparent;
  }
}
div.cell.selected.jupyter-soft-selected {
  border-left-width: 0;
  padding-left: 6px;
  background: linear-gradient(to right, #42A5F5 -40px, #42A5F5 7px, #E3F2FD 7px, #E3F2FD 100%);
}
.edit_mode div.cell.selected {
  border-color: #66BB6A;
  border-left-width: 0px;
  padding-left: 6px;
  background: linear-gradient(to right, #66BB6A -40px, #66BB6A 5px, transparent 5px, transparent 100%);
}
@media print {
  .edit_mode div.cell.selected {
    border-color: transparent;
  }
}
.prompt {
  /* This needs to be wide enough for 3 digit prompt numbers: In[100]: */
  min-width: 14ex;
  /* This padding is tuned to match the padding on the CodeMirror editor. */
  padding: 0.4em;
  margin: 0px;
  font-family: monospace;
  text-align: right;
  /* This has to match that of the the CodeMirror class line-height below */
  line-height: 1.21429em;
  /* Don't highlight prompt number selection */
  -webkit-touch-callout: none;
  -webkit-user-select: none;
  -khtml-user-select: none;
  -moz-user-select: none;
  -ms-user-select: none;
  user-select: none;
  /* Use default cursor */
  cursor: default;
}
@media (max-width: 540px) {
  .prompt {
    text-align: left;
  }
}
div.inner_cell {
  /* Old browsers */
  display: -webkit-box;
  -webkit-box-orient: vertical;
  -webkit-box-align: stretch;
  display: -moz-box;
  -moz-box-orient: vertical;
  -moz-box-align: stretch;
  display: box;
  box-orient: vertical;
  box-align: stretch;
  /* Modern browsers */
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  align-items: stretch;
  /* Old browsers */
  -webkit-box-flex: 1;
  -moz-box-flex: 1;
  box-flex: 1;
  /* Modern browsers */

}
@-moz-document url-prefix() {
  div.inner_cell {
    overflow-x: hidden;

}
/* input_area and input_prompt must match in top border and margin for alignment */
div.input_area {
  border: 1px solid #cfcfcf;

  background: #f7f7f7;
  line-height: 1.21429em;
}
/* This is needed so that empty prompt areas can collapse to zero height when there
   is no content in the output_subarea and the prompt. The main purpose of this is
   to make sure that empty JavaScript output_subareas have no height. */
div.prompt:empty {
  padding-top: 0;
  padding-bottom: 0;
}
div.unrecognized_cell {
  padding: 5px 5px 5px 0px;

/* The following gets added to the <head> if it is detected that the user has a
 * monospace font with inconsistent normal/bold/italic height.  See
 * notebookmain.js.  Such fonts will have keywords vertically offset with
 * respect to the rest of the text.  The user should select a better font.
 * See: https://github.com/ipython/ipython/issues/1503
 *
 * .CodeMirror span {
 *      vertical-align: bottom;
 * }
 */
.CodeMirror {
  line-height: 1.21429em;
  /* Changed from 1em to our global default */
  font-size: 14px;
  height: auto;
  /* Changed to auto to autogrow */
  background: none;
  /* Changed from white to allow our bg to show through */
}
.CodeMirror-scroll {
  /*  The CodeMirror docs are a bit fuzzy on if overflow-y should be hidden or visible.*/
  /*  We have found that if it is visible, vertical scrollbars appear with font size changes.*/
  overflow-y: hidden;
  overflow-x: auto;
}
.CodeMirror-lines {
  /* In CM2, this used to be 0.4em, but in CM3 it went to 4px. We need the em value because */
  /* we have set a different line-height and want this to scale with that. */
  padding: 0.4em;
}
.CodeMirror-linenumber {
  padding: 0 8px 0 4px;
}
.CodeMirror-gutters {
  border-bottom-left-radius: 2px;
  border-top-left-radius: 2px;
}
.CodeMirror pre {
  /* In CM3 this went to 4px from 0 in CM2. We need the 0 value because of how we size */
  /* .CodeMirror-lines */
  padding: 0;
  border: 0;
  border-radius: 0;
}

div.output_wrapper {

}
/* class for the output area when it should be height-limited */
div.output_scroll {

  height: 24em;

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><a href="https://catalogue.nlb.gov.sg/cgi-bin/spydus.exe/FULL/WPAC/BIBENQ/4014412/252276085,1"><img alt="Superminds by Thomas W Malone" src="https://wykeith.github.io/images/superminds.jpg" /></a></p>
<p>I just finished this book recently, and it sparked numerous ahha moments. Thus I highly recommend it for non-technical readers who are curious about AI and their impact on society. The author explains the concepts of superminds operating in society as a consequence of collective intelligence. He defines collective intelligence as the result of groups of individuals acting together in ways that seem intelligent or purposeful. This book teaches us how to recognise the characteristics of superminds and tap on their superpowers.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Basically There are 4 pure forms of superminds</p>
<ol>
<li><p><strong>Hierarchies</strong> - where people with authority make decisions others are required to follow. Found in businesses, nonprofit groups, and the operational parts of governments.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Democracies</strong> - where decisions are made by voting. Found in government, clubs, businesses and many other groups.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Markets</strong> - where decisions are made by mutual agreement among trading partners. Found whereever people trade money, goods, and services.</p>
</li>
<li><p><strong>Communities</strong> - where decisions are made by informal consensus or shared norms. Found throughout human life, from local neighborhoods to professional groups to national cultures.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p><font color="grey">
Another hybrid form of supermind supermind which encompasses all the above as well as indivdiuals is an eco-system
</font></p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Ecosystem</strong> where decisions are made based on who has the most power and the greatest ability to survive and reproduce. Found whereever there are no overall frameworks for cooperation, such as in the conflicts amony the different types of superminds above</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Advantages-&-Disadvantages">Advantages & Disadvantages<a class="anchor-link" href="#Advantages-&-Disadvantages">¶</a></h2><table>
<thead><tr>
<th>Type of Supermind</th>
<th>Cost of Group Decision Making</th>
<th>Benefits of Group Decision Making</th>
<th>Distribution of Benefits</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Hierarchy</td>
<td>Medium</td>
<td>High</td>
<td>Low</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Democracy</td>
<td>High</td>
<td>High</td>
<td>Medium</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Market</td>
<td>Medium +/-</td>
<td>Medium -</td>
<td>High</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Community</td>
<td>Medium</td>
<td>Medium</td>
<td>Medium</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Ecosystem</td>
<td>Low</td>
<td>Low</td>
<td>Low</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<ul>
<li><p>The minus sign in the medium +/- rating indicates that markets often have lower cost of decision making in large groups than other types (except ecosystem). Therefore as as information technologies continue to increase the size of groups that can make decisions together, it is very likely that markets will take over more of these decisions</p>
</li>
<li><p>Markets have "medium minus" benefits because participants in markets reap only one specific kind of benetfit from collective action: Buyers and sellers only trade with each other if they both think what they are getting is worth more to them than what they are giving up.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The book also discusses how technology improves each types of superminds into becoming better, smarter</p>
<h2 id="Some-examples-of-a-superminds-in-real-life">Some examples of a superminds in real life<a class="anchor-link" href="#Some-examples-of-a-superminds-in-real-life">¶</a></h2><ol>
<li>Our <em>Food production system</em> is a Market type of supermind. Previously in Hunting-Gathering communities , population growth was limited because we had to hunt, gather, prepare and cook our own food. Now we buy our food at stores and restaurant and outsourced most of the food preparation to a much larger supermind: the global market economy.</li>
</ol>
<blockquote><p>New information and transportation technology have increased our ability to take advantage economies of scale for food production and hence we have greatly increased the size of human groups , moving humans to the apex of the food chain</p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Purely hierarchical governments, with leaders like kings and emperors. have been overseeing markets for many years, and they still continue to do so in some countries today (ie vatican). But many countries have established democracies that oversee their hierarchical governments. Hierarchical governments are important. For instance with their legal system and police powers, they can resolve problems when people dont fulfill their contracts. They can also help prevent sellers from lying about their products, and they can insist on health and safety standards</li>
</ol>
<blockquote><p>Technology have enabled cyber-human sensing, as sensors become more purvasive more and more things will be electronically sensed and recorded in future. China is already experimenting with something it calls a social credit system which keep track of financial behavior, such as whether people keep up with their insurance premiums, tax payments, and credit card bills. The system is also expected to include information about various kinds of social behavior ie cheating on subway fares, jaywalking, causing disturbance on airline flights and violating family-planning limits. All this data is used to compute various "social credit" ratings that will lead to all kinds of benefits and penalties</p>
</blockquote>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="How-can-we-tap-on-superminds-to-solve-problems">How can we tap on superminds to solve problems<a class="anchor-link" href="#How-can-we-tap-on-superminds-to-solve-problems">¶</a></h2><ol>
<li>Hyperspecialisation - Topcoder,Amazon Mechanical Turk (Division of Human Tasks)</li>
<li>Contest Web , Wisdom of Crowds - Climate Colab (solving climate issues)</li>
<li>Task/Job Matching - Monster.com, Ebay (selling goods)</li>
</ol>
<p>Key features of technology enablers</p>
<ul>
<li>dividing work in new ways</li>
<li>assigning task in new ways</li>
<li>coordinating interdependencies among tasks in new ways</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="My-Thoughts-and-Takeways">My Thoughts and Takeways<a class="anchor-link" href="#My-Thoughts-and-Takeways">¶</a></h1><p>AI is also Augmented Intelligence, eventually technology will takeaway certain jobs but it will also create others.</p>
<ul>
<li>People will do what machines can't</li>
<li>People will do more of the things that machines make cheaper to do.</li>
<li>People will do things just because we want people to do them</li>
</ul>
<blockquote><p>Everyone should actively seek for opportunities to create cyber-human learning loops (this was my own masters dissertation topic 10 years ago!), Superminds that are made up of people and computers are be able to continuously improve their performance by learning from their own experiences extremely effectively. Superlearning can be achieved through superminds!</p>
</blockquote>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [1]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">time</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">os</span>
<span class="n">os</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">environ</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s2">"TZ"</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s2">"Asia/Singapore"</span>
<span class="n">time</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">tzset</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">time</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">ctime</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">
<div class="output_area"><div class="prompt output_prompt">Out[1]:</div>

<h1 id="Govtech-Chinese-New-Year-Code-breaking-challenge">Govtech Chinese New Year Code breaking challenge<a class="anchor-link" href="#Govtech-Chinese-New-Year-Code-breaking-challenge">¶</a></h1><p><img alt="Govtech Challenge" src="http://oi67.tinypic.com/5ug55d.jpg" /></p>
<h2 id="Govtech-is-running-a-coding-challenge-to-give-away-some-prizes">Govtech is running a coding challenge to give away some prizes<a class="anchor-link" href="#Govtech-is-running-a-coding-challenge-to-give-away-some-prizes">¶</a></h2><p>Decided to give it a shot since I'm bored with CNY festivities in lala land.
Answer to the code is at the end of the post =), you can also
submit your answer by 11:59 pm, February 8 here: <a href="https://bit.ly/2RUVNBG">https://bit.ly/2RUVNBG</a>.</p>
<p>Do give me credit (^.^)</p>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="Clues">Clues<a class="anchor-link" href="#Clues">¶</a></h1><ul>
<li>The punctuations marks are unobfuscated</li>
<li>Exclamation mark at the end of sentence and period is at the end of a word</li>
<li>there are no capital letters, all are lowercase or punctuations</li>
<li>The encryption could be two ways, forward and backwards, assuming this is a symmetric-key encryption without the need for any key exchange process </li>
</ul>
<p>we try to guess 'i' in the cyphertext which could be a single letter english word as well as other 2 letter and 3 letter words containing the letter 'i'</p>
<ol>
<li>i</li>
<li>ip</li>
<li>ivl</li>
<li>gmiz</li>
<li>pixxg</li>
</ol>
<p>Frequency analysis methods illustrated here as well <a href="https://www3.nd.edu/~busiforc/handouts/cryptography/cryptography%20hints.html">https://www3.nd.edu/~busiforc/handouts/cryptography/cryptography%20hints.html</a></p>
<p>One-Letter English Words : a, I.
Since it doesnt make sense to decapitalise a word , we map the letter a to i and try with the longer words</p>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [1]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Difference </span>
<span class="k">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">"The difference in alphatical order between a and i is {}"</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">format</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">ord</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'a'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="nb">ord</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'i'</span><span class="p">)))</span>

<span class="c1"># Add difference</span>
<span class="k">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">"Adding the differnce makes ip become {}{}!"</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">format</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">chr</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">ord</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'i'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">8</span><span class="p">),</span><span class="nb">chr</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">ord</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'p'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">8</span><span class="p">)))</span>

<span class="c1"># Try ivl</span>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="What-type-of-Power-GenCo-package-is-better:-variable-or-fixed?">What type of Power GenCo package is better: variable or fixed?<a class="anchor-link" href="#What-type-of-Power-GenCo-package-is-better:-variable-or-fixed?">¶</a></h1><p><img alt="Tariff Components" src="https://keith.ml/images/SP_Tariff_Q42018.png" title="SP Q4-2018 Tarif Component">
<a href="https://www.spgroup.com.sg/wcm/connect/spgrp/4eb90582-069e-419a-b371-f1dd9a141a7a/%5B20180929%5D+Media+Release+-+Electricity+Tariff+Revision+for+the+period+1+Oct+to+Dec+2018.pdf?MOD=AJPERES">Link to Chart</a></img></p>
<p>Come 1st November, Singapore's retail electicity market will be liberalised. The electricity market will be a fully competitive market. Various power generating companies are now offering different packages to supply eletricity to the retail consumer. Honestly I think all the packages are confusing, with hidden costs like GST and Lost Transmission Factor these are not presented upfront to the consumer. Rather than comparing the indiviual pricing of all the packages which will be subject to change, I'll go through an anaylsis to make an informed choice of either a variable rate or fixed rate package.</p>
<p>It is worthwhile to note that if one were to stick to the incumbent SPPower , one would have paid addition premium as all other gencos are offering discounts off SP regulated tariff rates. Does this mean SP will be pressured to lower their domestic tariff rates causing a race condition for others to supply free electricity? Short answer is no as there are also business consumers which account for 80% of electricity demand.</p>
<p>The electricity tariff comprises two key components – fuel cost and non-fuel cost.</p>
<p>The fuel cost of 76.1% is tied to oil prices by commercial contracts, which change depending on global market conditions. The non-fuel cost is the cost of generating and delivering electricity to homes. Network cost forms a substantial part of this component at 22.0%</p>
<p>The 2 main cost components that determine the electrical tariff are the network cost and the fuel cost. Since the network cost is pretty much fixed upfront capex. The variability in tariff will be impacted by the fuel cost rather than the network cost.</p>
<p>Data.gov.sg publishs the fuel mix data for electricity generation. We observe that LNG accounts on average about 95% of the fuelmix. With this we shall study the LNG pricing closely.</p>
<p>A free source of LNG prices that can be downloaded from Quandl. There are from three major LNG futures exchanges in the world. Japan, US and Europe. Links to download them appended below</p>
<p>Since LNG pricing is recorded in USD , we should account for exchange rate flucation.
The USDSGD exchange rates can be sourced from MAS' Exchange rate end point api</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>Model predicts that the LNG prices are trending down</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [20]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># We fit a linear regression model to project a tariff rate based </span>
<span class="c1"># on a single input of price</span>


<span class="n">df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">merge</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">norm_fuel</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">domestic_rates</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">on</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'month'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">how</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'left'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dropna</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="n">y</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[[</span><span class="s1">'rate'</span><span class="p">]]</span>
<span class="n">X</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[[</span><span class="s1">'sgd_value'</span><span class="p">]]</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [21]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">sklearn.model_selection</span> <span class="k">import</span> <span class="n">train_test_split</span>
<span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">sklearn.linear_model</span> <span class="k">import</span> <span class="n">LinearRegression</span>

<span class="n">X_train</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">X_test</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y_train</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y_test</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">train_test_split</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">X</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">y</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">test_size</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.3</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">random_state</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">lm</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">LinearRegression</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">lm</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">fit</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">X_train</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">y_train</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Goodness of fit</span>
<span class="nb">print</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'R-Square: </span><span class="se">\n</span><span class="s1">'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">lm</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">score</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">X</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">y</span><span class="p">))</span>

<span class="n">predictions</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">lm</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predict</span><span class="p">(</span> <span class="n">X_test</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">scatter</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">y_test</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">predictions</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">xlabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Actual Y'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">ylabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Predicted Y'</span><span class="p">)</span>

<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">combined</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">concat</span><span class="p">([</span><span class="n">forecast</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'ds'</span><span class="p">],</span><span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">lm</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predict</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">forecast</span><span class="p">[[</span><span class="s1">'yhat_lower'</span><span class="p">]])),</span><span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">lm</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">predict</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">forecast</span><span class="p">[[</span><span class="s1">'yhat_upper'</span><span class="p">]]))],</span><span class="n">axis</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">combined</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">columns</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Date'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Predicted_lower'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Predicted_upper'</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">search</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">combined</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">dropna</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_index</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Date'</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Genco floating rate plan</span>
<span class="n">discount_factor</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mf">0.79</span>
<span class="c1"># We discount the upper confidence interval by the tariff discount rate</span>
<span class="n">search</span><span class="p">[[</span><span class="s1">'Discount_upper'</span><span class="p">]]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">search</span><span class="p">[[</span><span class="s1">'Predicted_upper'</span><span class="p">]]</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="n">discount_factor</span>


<span class="n">start</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">search</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">searchsorted</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">datetime</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">2018</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">11</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">end</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">search</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">index</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">searchsorted</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">datetime</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">2020</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">11</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">search</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">iloc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">start</span><span class="p">:</span><span class="n">end</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">6</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">axhline</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mf">16.88</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'r'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linestyle</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'--'</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">ylabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Tariff $/Kwh'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">text</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'2019-01-01'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">17</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Genco X Fixed'</span><span class="p">)</span>

</pre></div>

<div class="output_area"><div class="prompt"></div>

">
</img></div>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="Observations">Observations<a class="anchor-link" href="#Observations">¶</a></h1><ul>
<li>If the regulated tariffs rises above the upper band of the projected confidence internal, the discountd rates may never fall below the fixed rate of 16.88. Hence Genco X's fix rate is set fairly as it also touches the lower band of the projected confidence interval.</li>
<li>For cashflow budgeting certainty , one would go for a fixed rate package</li>
<li>If we believe that the regulated tariffs will fall inbetween the confidence intervals, there is a possibiliity that discounted rates may be cheaper than the fixed rate, one should go for a variable rate package instead. This is also assuming that electricity consumption is high enough to realise sizeable savings.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>

</pre></div>

<h1 id="Datascience-exercise-#1">Datascience exercise #1<a class="anchor-link" href="#Datascience-exercise-#1">¶</a></h1><p><img alt="Chart showing errors in height estimates" src="https://wykeith.github.io/images/height-survey-boxplot.png" /></p>
<p>Attended a basic R tutorial for my MUSPP class, everyone was tasked to estimate the heights of each other and record them into a table. This formed the dataset which we subsequently analysed using R. I'm repeating this exercise in Python as it is easier for me for analysis. Since I cant use python as the class assignments are based on R, I will try to do the python recoding for all my future assignments on this blog.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Observations">Observations<a class="anchor-link" href="#Observations">¶</a></h2><ul>
<li>Generally most of us under-estimate</li>
<li>With the exception of MaKaKu who tend to mostly over-estimate </li>
<li>Yours truly understimates everyone's height, and since I'm consistently inaccurate, one could add 10cm to all future predictions from myself to achieve an estimate that is closer to reality. Maybe I have got parallex error in my vision.</li>
<li>Plotting the all errors for each estimates individually, we also find that for the shortest (DeKo), most of the estimators over-estimate, ie more blue bars. And for the tallest (LiSwKi) most of the estimators under-estimate, ie more orange bars. See chart below</li>
</ul>
<p>Takeaway if estimators were IOT sensors, the above chart can be used to visualise under-estimation/over-estimations during calibration.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<h1 id="We-should-plot-the-sum-of-all-errors-VS-actual-heights-in-a-single-chart-to-see-this-clearly.">We should plot the sum of all errors VS actual heights in a single chart to see this clearly.<a class="anchor-link" href="#We-should-plot-the-sum-of-all-errors-VS-actual-heights-in-a-single-chart-to-see-this-clearly.">¶</a></h1>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="Key-Insight">Key Insight<a class="anchor-link" href="#Key-Insight">¶</a></h1><p>From the limited observations everyone is generally good at estimating heights between 165-170. 
<strong> There is a strong correlation r-value = -0.92 between errors and actual heights.</strong> Suggesting that that there is over-estimating for shorter people and underestimating for taller people.</p>
<hr>
</hr></div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="Additional-Code---Plot-out-individual-estimators-and-their-estimates">Additional Code - Plot out individual estimators and their estimates<a class="anchor-link" href="#Additional-Code---Plot-out-individual-estimators-and-their-estimates">¶</a></h1>
<pre><code>for x in actual_heights.sort_values('Act_value').Person:
    Target = x
    xline = actual_heights.query('Person==@Target')['Act_value']
    ## Line represents actual height
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
    fig =  sns.barplot(data=merged_table[merged_table.Person==Target].sort_values('Est_value'),y='Estimator',x='Est_value',color=".7")
    plt.axvline(int(xline),c='r',linestyle='-.',lw=1)
    plt.xlim(int(xline)-40, int(xline)+40)
    plt.title("Grp Estimated Heights for {}".format(Target))
    plt.xlabel("Heights (cm)")
    plt.ylabel("Estimators")

    plt.show(fig)</code></pre>

<h1 id="What-are-some-of-the-posting-patterns-on-the-DS-Connect-group-?">What are some of the posting patterns on the DS-Connect group ?<a class="anchor-link" href="#What-are-some-of-the-posting-patterns-on-the-DS-Connect-group-?">¶</a></h1><p><img alt="Bokeh" src="https://wykeith.github.io/images/ds-graph.png" /></p>
<ol>
<li>Been rather busy on the new job lately, didnt have much time to mantain this blog.</li>
<li>Recently there was a visualisation challenge posted on OnePublicService DataScience group on facebook's workplace</li>
<li>Unfortunately a tableau viz beat my entry over the most likes.</li>
<li>Nevertheless I thought it would be useful to explain the visualisation and workings.</li>
<li>"Keeping It Simple" is always a good principle to follow for any visualisation.</li>
</ol>
<p>Some observations as follows</p>
<ul>
<li>Govtech (Blue) users frequently posts mid-day 12pm-6pm Tues-Tues</li>
<li>SCDF (Purple) users has bigger posts outside weekdays office hours - PSDm,Mindef,CSC,MoM are after-office-hours only posters</li>
<li>CPF (Orange) users posts are more frequent in the morning before 8am</li>
<li>Bigger posts are usually submitted in latter half of the day (afternoon)</li>
<li>Hardcore Govtech users posting at 1-2am at night</li>
<li>During Weekend afternoons the group becomes a ghost town</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>

    <span class="k">elif</span> <span class="n">Type</span> <span class="o">==</span> <span class="s2">"Reactions"</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">data</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">color</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">normalize</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">merged</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">Reactions</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">Base</span><span class="p">),</span><span class="s1">'green'</span>

<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="Housing-affordability">Housing affordability<a class="anchor-link" href="#Housing-affordability">¶</a></h1><p><img alt="Logo" src="http://cdn-cms.pgimgs.com/news/2016/09/Figure-1-SIBOR-SOR-Charts-v2-e1474855552532-1024x620.jpg" /></p>
<ol>
<li>It has been reported in the <a href="http://www.businesstimes.com.sg/real-estate/hdb-resale-prices-retreat-06-m-o-m-in-july-but-volume-up-18-srx">papers</a> that resales prices are coming down</li>
<li>Interest rates for bank housing loans are on the rise together with the possible Fed rate hike and sibor increase.</li>
<li>Recently I've booked a new flat from HDB however HDB is dragging their feet in confirming the followup appointment for finalising the sales agreement, I'm considering the purchase a ready resale unit instead forgoing the 2k option fee.</li>
<li>Three years ago resale prices were high and especially so for matured estates. I couldnt afford a resale flat to be near my parents so I had to rent and travel around like a nomad. It is really tiring and difficult especially when you have children.</li>
<li>It will be useful to evalute if the rental cost + the cost of a new BTO unit would still be cheaper than purchasing a similar resale unit.</li>
<li>We shall try to find out if a typical household with dual median income is able to afford a median resale flat in Singapore with only a CPF loan/bank loan without monthly cash topups.</li>
<li>Fortunately <a href="https://data.gov.sg/dataset/resale-flat-prices">Data.gov.sg</a> offers HDB resale transcations data from 1990 to current month</li>
<li>While <a href="http://stats.mom.gov.sg/Pages/Income-Summary-Table.aspx">MoM</a> provides a spreadsheet download of the annual median wage for Singapore residents from 2001-2016</li>
<li>It is noted that ownership of HDB resale flats are only avaliable to both Singapore PRs and citizens, so it safe to assume HDB resale transactions are conducted between Singapore residents and the median income used to compute the maximum CPF loan is ceiling representative of a general Singapore house buyer.</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">

</div>

<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Parse HDB Data</span>
<span class="c1"># Combining all the downloaded csv together</span>
<span class="c1">#  - 'Resale transacted prices.'</span>
<span class="c1">#  - 'Prior to March 2012, data is based on date of approval for the resale transactions.'</span>
<span class="c1">#  - 'For March 2012 onwards, the data is based on date of registration for the resale</span>
<span class="c1">#    transactions.'</span>

<span class="n">dfa</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">csvafilename</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">parse_dates</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'month'</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">header</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">dfb</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">csvbfilename</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">parse_dates</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'month'</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">header</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">dfc</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">csvcfilename</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">parse_dates</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'month'</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="n">header</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">concat</span><span class="p">([</span><span class="n">dfc</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">dfb</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">dfa</span><span class="p">],</span><span class="n">axis</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">)</span>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Parse MoM Data</span>

<span class="n">headers</span> <span class="o">=</span>  <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Total_CPF'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'FullTime'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Parttime'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Total_noCPF'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'FullTime_noCPF'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Parttime_noCPF'</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">xls</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_excel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">xlsxfilename</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">index_col</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">header</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">None</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">names</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">headers</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">skiprows</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">7</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">skip_footer</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">8</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">na_values</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'n.a.'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">reset_index</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Drop everything else , only interested in Gross Wage excluding employeers CPF</span>

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># NPV of a series of cashflows ,with interest compounded annually</span>
<span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">NPV</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="n">mthpay</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">100</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">yrs</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">30</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">start</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">pa</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.1</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="nb">sum</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">0</span>
    <span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">x</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">range</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">int</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">start</span><span class="p">),</span><span class="nb">int</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">start</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="nb">abs</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">yrs</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">))):</span>
        <span class="nb">sum</span> <span class="o">+=</span> <span class="n">mthpay</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="n">pa</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">**</span><span class="n">x</span> <span class="c1">#Simple monthly interest</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="nb">sum</span>

<span class="n">OArate</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.23</span>
<span class="n">yrsloan</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">25</span>
<span class="n">intrate</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.026</span>
<span class="n">NfYperhouse</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">2</span>

<span class="c1"># Use Fulltime wages without employer CFP , ammount that goes into CPFOA account is 23% from Yr 2010 onwards</span>
<span class="n">totalCPFloan</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">totalCPFloan</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Year'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">income</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">totalCPFloan</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'FullTime_noCPF'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">income</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'FullTime_noCPF'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">map</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="k">lambda</span> <span class="n">x</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">NPV</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">mthpay</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">NfYperhouse</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="n">OArate</span><span class="p">),</span><span class="n">yrs</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">yrsloan</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">pa</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">intrate</span><span class="p">))</span>

<span class="n">OArate</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.23</span>
<span class="n">yrsloan</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">30</span>
<span class="n">intrate</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.01</span>

<span class="c1"># Use Fulltime wages without employer CFP , ammount that goes into CPFOA account is 23% from Yr 2010 onwards</span>
<span class="n">totalBANKloan</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">()</span>

<h2 id="Notes:">Notes:<a class="anchor-link" href="#Notes:">¶</a></h2><ol>
<li>For a 25 year CPF loan, the largest a typical median household in singapore can generally afford is a 3 room resale flat.</li>
<li>Resale prices peaked between 2013 and 2014. </li>
<li>This peak of 2014 exceeded the peak in 1997 (Asian financial crisis)</li>
<li>Between 2010 and 2014 median resale prices were rising faster than median wage growth. </li>
<li>As such median resale flats of all types were <strong>NOT</strong> within reach of typical families with 25yr CPF loans @ 2.6% interests.</li>
<li>It seems that resale prices have stabilised over the past 2 years</li>
<li><strong>TODO</strong>: Integrate volume of transactions over time</li>
<li><strong>TODO</strong>: See if there are any trends if we normalise the price by the area</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">

</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Annex">Annex<a class="anchor-link" href="#Annex">¶</a></h3><p><a href="http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/hdb-shortens-homebuyers-loan-tenure-25-years">http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/hdb-shortens-homebuyers-loan-tenure-25-years</a></p>
<p>Published  5:34 PM, August 27, 2013<br>
Updated 9:50 AM, August 28, 2013</br></p>
<p>SINGAPORE — With immediate effect, the Housing and Development Board (HDB) has shortened its maximum loan tenure to 25 years and the mortgage servicing ratio (MSR) limit has also been cut to 30 per cent of the borrower’s gross monthly salary.</p>
<p>Previously, HDB loan tenures were at 30 years and the MSR limit was at 35 per cent of the borrower’s gross monthly salary.</p>
<p>From tomorrow (Aug 28), financial institutions will in tandem reduce the maximum tenure of new housing loans and re-financing facilities from 35 years to 30 years.</p>
<p>With immediate effect as well, Permanent Residents (PR) who want to buy resale flats will have to wait three years after receiving their PR status. Prior to this change, they could buy a flat as soon as they received PR status.</p>
<p>Announcing these changes today, the HDB also provided more details of the extension of the Special Housing Grant (SHG) and the new step-up housing grant, which Prime Minster Lee Hsien Loong first announced during the National Day Rally.</p>
<p>The income ceiling for SHG will be raised significantly, from S\$2,250 a month to S\$6,500 a month for families and S\$3,250 for singles. Mr Lee previously announced that the SHG would be extended to middle-income households and could be used for buying new four-room flats.</p>
<p>Under the new step up grant, families who want to upgrade from a two-room to a three-room flat can get a housing grant of S$15,000.</p>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p><img alt="Causal loop diagram" src="https://wykeith.github.io/images/CL-Slide1.JPG" title="Causal loop diagram of Changi Airport" /></p>
<ol>
<li>There is a common saying : the past does not define our future</li>
<li>Previously I patched together a simple trend analysis model of passenger throughput based on past observations of similar data (to the availability of publicly accessible data) and subsequently projecting them forward into the future with a confidence interval. </li>
<li>It is an naive assumption that there are no other factors involved, a simplistic understanding of growth.</li>
<li>In the real world there are numerous complex interacting causes and effects (ie more growth may led to subsequently less growth if not managed well). In order to understand such complex relationships , I shall utilise casual loop diagrams.</li>
<li>Above shows an initial causal loop sketch for changi airport strung together manually in powerpoint. Blue indicates positive relationships, red implies a inverse relatioship.</li>
<li>The relationships are subsequently coded into a graph database for my further analysis</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [27]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">pos_relationship</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Airport Tax'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Infrastructure Investment'</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Passenger Volume'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Airport Tax'</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Infrastructure Investment'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Excess Terminal Capacity'</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Excess of Demand for Air Travel'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Air-ticket Price'</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Quality of Service'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Air Travel (Demand)'</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Local Population'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Air Travel (Demand)'</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Excess Terminal Capacity'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Quality of Service'</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Excess Terminal Capacity'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Attractiveness of Terminal'</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Air Travel (Demand)'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Passenger Volume'</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Passenger Volume'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Airport Tax'</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Passenger Volume'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Excess of Demand for Air Travel'</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Passenger Volume'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Growth of Region'</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Attractiveness of Terminal'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'New Entrants'</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Air Travel Services (Supply)'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Avaliable Destinations'</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Avaliable Destinations'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Excess of Demand for Air Travel'</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Growth of Region'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Avaliable Destinations'</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'New Entrants'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Number of Airplanes'</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'New Entrants'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Quality of Service'</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Number of Airplanes'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Air Travel Services (Supply)'</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="p">]</span>

<span class="n">neg_relationship</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Air-ticket Price'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Air Travel (Demand)'</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Air Travel Services (Supply)'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Excess Terminal Capacity'</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Air Travel Services (Supply)'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Excess of Demand for Air Travel'</span><span class="p">],</span>
    <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'Excess of Demand for Air Travel'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'Quality of Service'</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="p">]</span>

<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">relation</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">pos_relationship</span><span class="p">:</span>
    <span class="n">re</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">Relationship</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">Node</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'item'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">title</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">relation</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]),</span> <span class="s2">"S"</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Node</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'item'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">title</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">relation</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]),</span> <span class="n">Direction</span><span class="o">=+</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">graph</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">merge</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">re</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">relation</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">neg_relationship</span><span class="p">:</span>
    <span class="n">re</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">Relationship</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">Node</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'item'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">title</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">relation</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]),</span> <span class="s2">"O"</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">Node</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'item'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">title</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">relation</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]),</span> <span class="n">Direction</span><span class="o">=-</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
    <span class="n">graph</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">merge</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">re</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Longest-chain-in-the-network">Longest chain in the network<a class="anchor-link" href="#Longest-chain-in-the-network">¶</a></h2><p><img alt="Causal loop diagram" src="https://wykeith.github.io/images/CL-Slide3.png" title="Longest loop Chain">
Just for fun , I wanted to know what is the longest path I can walk, not re-visiting any nodes and arriving back to the same place without changing direction of the relationships. 11 nodes is the longest discovered by the graph query.</img></p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Look-for-a-reinforcing-or-virtuous-loop">Look for a reinforcing or virtuous loop<a class="anchor-link" href="#Look-for-a-reinforcing-or-virtuous-loop">¶</a></h2><p><img alt="Causal loop diagram" src="https://wykeith.github.io/images/CL-Slide4.png" title="Virtuous loop Chain" /></p>
<p>When there is an investment in airport infrastucture it leads to increase in airport capacity which then improves services levels. Better service levels brings in more passengers and hence increase in revenue for the airport to improve infrastructure. Improvement in airport infrastructre will also attract new airlines to fly through, this increases competition which will also bring up service levels to attact more customers</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Then-a-balancing-or-vicious-loop">Then a balancing or vicious loop<a class="anchor-link" href="#Then-a-balancing-or-vicious-loop">¶</a></h2><p><img alt="Causal loop diagram" src="https://wykeith.github.io/images/CL-Slide5.png" title="Vicious loop Chain" /></p>
<p>On the other hand , increasing passenger volumes will lead to crowding of the airports bringing down the excess demand for travelling and the lowering of quality of service provided. This provides a counter-balance to the revenue/investment loop above.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Graph-analysis---Centrality">Graph analysis - Centrality<a class="anchor-link" href="#Graph-analysis---Centrality">¶</a></h2><p>Centrality measures give us relative measures of importance in the network. There are many different centrality measures and each measures a different type of “importance. In graph theory, eigenvector centrality (also called eigencentrality) is a measure of the influence of a node in a network. It assigns relative scores to all nodes in the network based on the concept that connections to high-scoring nodes contribute more to the score of the node in question than equal connections to low-scoring nodes.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [28]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">igraph</span> <span class="k">import</span> <span class="n">Graph</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="n">IGraph</span>

<span class="n">query</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s1">'''</span>
<span class="s1">MATCH (c1)-[r]->(c2)</span>
<span class="s1">RETURN ID(c1), ID(c2), r.Direction AS weight</span>
<span class="s1">'''</span>

<span class="n">ig</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">IGraph</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">TupleList</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">graph</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">run</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">query</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="n">weights</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [29]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1">#pg = ig.personalized_pagerank(niter=10000)</span>
<span class="n">pg</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">ig</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">eigenvector_centrality</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">pgvs</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[]</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">p</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="nb">zip</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ig</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">vs</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">pg</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="n">pgvs</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">append</span><span class="p">({</span><span class="s2">"ID"</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">p</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">][</span><span class="s2">"name"</span><span class="p">],</span> <span class="s2">"pg"</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="n">p</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]})</span>

<span class="n">write_clusters_query</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s1">'''</span>
<span class="s1">UNWIND </span><span class="si">{nodes}</span><span class="s1"> AS n</span>
<span class="s1">MATCH (c) WHERE ID(c) = n.ID</span>
<span class="s1">SET c.value = n.pg</span>
<span class="s1">'''</span>

<span class="n">graph</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">run</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">write_clusters_query</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">nodes</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">pgvs</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output">
<div class="output_area"><div class="prompt output_prompt">Out[29]:</div>
<div class="output_text output_subarea output_execute_result">
<pre><py2neo.database.cursor at 0x7fccfc042320></pre>
</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="inner_cell">

<h2 id="Important-Nodes-in-our-Causal-Loops">Important Nodes in our Causal Loops<a class="anchor-link" href="#Important-Nodes-in-our-Causal-Loops">¶</a></h2><p><img alt="Causal loop diagram" src="https://wykeith.github.io/images/CL-Slide6.png" title="Centrai" /></p>

<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="c1"># Bar chart to compare the relative importance of each node</span>
<span class="n">query</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s2">"MATCH (a) RETURN a.title AS title, a.value AS value"</span>
<span class="n">df</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">DataFrame</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">graph</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">data</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">query</span><span class="p">))</span>

<span class="n">fig</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sort_values</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">by</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'value'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">inplace</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">True</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_index</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'title'</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">value</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">kind</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'barh'</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_xlabel</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Centrality Values'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_title</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">'Ranking of Factors'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Notes:">Notes:<a class="anchor-link" href="#Notes:">¶</a></h3><ol>
<li>Pertaining to the development of airports , this model shows the most important factors that can influence our planning.</li>
<li>It seems that local population is not a key dominant determinant in airport planning , due to it's limited relationship with the other factors. If I create more links to the other nodes , then it's centrality value or importance will increase.</li>
<li>Casual Loops can help us to identify systemic risks or unintended effects, ie the reinforcing loop and balancing loops both impacting capacity and quality of service differently</li>
<li>Quantitative econometric models can then be built based on these diagrams, which I hope to explore futher.</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="How-can-we-do-forecasting-in-an-environment-of-uncertainty?">How can we do forecasting in an environment of uncertainty?<a class="anchor-link" href="#How-can-we-do-forecasting-in-an-environment-of-uncertainty?">¶</a></h2><p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fan_chart_(time_series)"><img alt="Logo" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/83/FanChartInfl.jpg" title="Hypothetical Fan Chart of the Inflation Rate" /></a></p>
<ol>
<li>This was one of questions brought up as a topic during a long overdue course on systems engineering I'm currently attending @ work.</li>
<li>We were introduced to monte carlo simulations in excel (not for betting in casinos). It is basically a tool to guage the outcome/payout/projections with randomisations to input parameters over large multiple runs >1000 .</li>
<li>I'm curious to the effects of the selection of probability distributions on such outcomes.</li>
<li>This will also be useful for my own notes on machine learning where sample data is fitted into a unknown assumed population distribution.</li>
<li>There is a also recently released opensource Forecasting tool from facebook - Prophet that could be adapted for forcasting purposes, we shall benchmark against it.</li>
<li>As I have studied changi airport previously , I will continue to base this experiment on forcasting the monthly air passenger arrivals in Changi.</li>
<li>Partly because aggregated monthly data since year 1961 is freely avaliable from data.gov.sg </li>
<li>Welcome all views below in the comments section</li>
</ol>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">mthrange</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">20</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="mi">12</span>
<span class="n">noofruns</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">1000</span>
<span class="n">seed</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">2017</span>

<span class="n">dates_list</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">as_matrix</span><span class="p">([</span><span class="s1">'month'</span><span class="p">])</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">flatten</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">date_start</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">dates_list</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">date_end</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">dates_list</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="n">relativedelta</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">months</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">mthrange</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In [4]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">xkcd</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Setup variables</span>
<span class="n">x</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">mdates</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">date2num</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">as_matrix</span><span class="p">([</span><span class="s1">'month'</span><span class="p">])</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">flatten</span><span class="p">())</span>
<span class="n">y</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">as_matrix</span><span class="p">([</span><span class="s1">'no_of_air_passenger_arrivals'</span><span class="p">])</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">flatten</span><span class="p">()</span>

<span class="c1"># Use Polynomial fit</span>
<span class="c1"># Perhaps there is some inflection</span>
<span class="n">z</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">polyfit</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">y</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">p</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">poly1d</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">z</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Predict Arrival at 2035 based on our polynomial fit</span>
<span class="n">x2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">np</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">append</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">mdates</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">date2num</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">date_end</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">y2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">p</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x2</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Format the Graph</span>
<span class="n">fig</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">figure</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">15</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">20</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplot2grid</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">ax2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplot2grid</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">),</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">))</span>

<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_xlabel</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="s2">"Year"</span><span class="p">),</span><span class="n">size</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">16</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_ylabel</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="s2">"Passenger Arrivals"</span><span class="p">),</span><span class="n">size</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">16</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">yaxis</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_major_formatter</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">FuncFormatter</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="k">lambda</span> <span class="n">x</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">tick</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">str</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="nb">int</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="mi">1000000</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="s1">'mil'</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_ylim</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">as_matrix</span><span class="p">([</span><span class="s1">'no_of_air_passenger_arrivals'</span><span class="p">])</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">max</span><span class="p">()</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">ax2</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">xaxis</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_major_formatter</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">FuncFormatter</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="k">lambda</span> <span class="n">x</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">tick</span><span class="p">:</span> <span class="nb">str</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x</span><span class="o">*</span><span class="mi">100</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="s1">'%'</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">ax2</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_xlabel</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="s2">"Growth Mth-on-Mth"</span><span class="p">),</span><span class="n">size</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">16</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax2</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_xlim</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="o">-</span><span class="mf">0.4</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="mf">0.4</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax2</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_ylabel</span><span class="p">((</span><span class="s2">"Frequency"</span><span class="p">),</span><span class="n">size</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">16</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot_date</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'month'</span><span class="p">],</span><span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'no_of_air_passenger_arrivals'</span><span class="p">],</span><span class="n">fmt</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'-'</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x2</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">y2</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="s1">'r--'</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="n">ROC</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">df</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">'no_of_air_passenger_arrivals'</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">pct_change</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">ROC</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">hist</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">bins</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">30</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">grid</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="kc">False</span><span class="p">)</span>

<span class="c1"># Visualise the graph</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">legend</span><span class="p">([</span><span class="s1">'Actual'</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">'Trend'</span> <span class="p">],</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">'upper left'</span><span class="p">,</span><span class="n">fontsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
